  "id": "urn:kernel-v1:break.malfunction",
  "label": "break.malfunction (X breaks Y — Y stops being able to do what it is for, though it stays in one piece; as in \"break the alarm clock\", NOT as in \"break a glass\" or \"break a promise\")",
  "status": "research-grade",
  "pattern": "sense-scoped destructive event: doing -> loss of function without loss of unity (design §1.3 row break.malfunction)",
  "gloss": "X did something to Y at some time; before this time people can do things with Y; because of what X did, after this time people cannot do things with Y; Y is still one something.",
  "notes": "Authored fresh; the v0 word-level break explication could NOT cover this sense (its many-small-pieces clause misdescribes a broken machine — the v0 authoring note said so). Agentive frame (Render_nonfunctional: \"You broke the alarm clock\"); the inchoative 'the lawn mower finally broke' (v-01372011) has a different argument structure and per R3(c) is NOT clustered here — it stays in excludedSenses, mintable later as its own sense. KNOWN-WEAK: 'what Y is for' is rendered extensionally as 'people can do things with Y'; the purpose/design nuance is dropped.",
